description.text:
RummiKub (supports more players)

inspired by http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1428474

  1. There are two sizes of tiles, a travel size and the 30% larger original size.
  2. Each color has two sets of numbers but only one joker, as laid out in kit.
  3. STL's are grouped into logical print jobs.
  4. Print inserts upside down so shinny, flared out side is facing out (fits in tile better too).
  5. Inserts designed to snap in with moderate pressure from fingers or smooth object.
  6. Suggest the tolerance test first to confirm how well inserts fit into tiles.
  7. Official game rack holds 24 tiles, my large rack holds 35 tiles.
  8. How to play: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rummikub
  9. I included the underline inserts for 6 & 9 tiles, but decided not to use them on mine.

WHY??? The original game only supports up to 4 players (4 colors) and we always have more that want to play. I figured we can support more people by adding additional colors. We'll use the original game for 2-3 players and the printed version for 4-6+ players. I'll be printing a 6th color very soon.

Print Settings

2 shells for everything

TILES

.30 Nozzle, .20 layer height, 30% fill, 4 solid bottom and 4 solid top layers

NUMBERS

The numbers can have less solid layers, but same resolution as tiles.

Print 2 tile sets for each set of numbers (a color set). Only 1 joker for each color.

NOTE: If your filament is more transparent, you may need more than 4 layers to prevent see-through..

Large Rack (for Original Tiles)

2-Large_Rack_Side (per player)
5-Large_Rack_Holder (per player)
3 or 4-Large_Rack_Support (per rack)
This rack is for the original sized tiles. Tolerance adjusted for LOW resolution, fast printing. All rack pieces print at .40 nozzle, .30 layer height, 20% fill. 3 solid layers on top, but only 2 solid layers on bottom. This rack holds at least 30 tiles.

Travel Rack

This one part was remixed from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1428474
It was to large for my print bed so I cut it in half in a zigzag shape for an easy glue job. I did not print this as I wanted the larger tiles and collapsing rack for myself.

Updates

06/17/16:: Added V2 of Large_Rack_Holder, with Key Hole in end, and added Large_Rack_Tray_Latch, which is a small key to keep tray from sliding out of right side. New pic of rack assy shows the right side where the changes took place.

title: Miniature Paint Brush Stand / Organization Tray

description.text:
This is a stand/organizer for miniature paint brushes (or any small paint brushes).

The 3 trays in the front can be used for anything, my intention is to use the 2 smaller ones for water for cleaning brushes after painting, and the larger one for a dry sponge or paper towels for dry brushing, but they could be used for anything.

I have read various reports of prints not being water tight. I used just a 2 layer wall thickness and the trays appeared to hold water just fine. I primed and painted them though just to try and make sure and seal small cracks were water might leak.

The paint also acted as an adhesive to hold the 4 pieces together better. If it hadn't my intention was to use a hot glue gun and glue everything together. Permanently fixing the pieces together isn't required, it just makes the top more stable as there is a slight amount of slop with the risers and the slots they go into.

Swag in style with the subtle Hylian accent brandishing your wallet. This wallet features two slots that can comfortably hold 4* of your dearest cards close to you. Story

I've been using dadhoc's Another Slim Wallet with MetroCard Slot for just over a year, and it's been great. My cards loved it, and it relaxed over the months. The old cards were replaced with new ones, and the new cards started viewing the wallet as more of a prison. The pressures of life and my pocket started to take their toll on the little PLA child, and things started creaking. Due to poor layer bonding, the 'bars' of 'the cage' cracked, and later snapped away. A new design was needed.

description.text:
I am uploading this very simple but very useful object due to repeated requests. This accuracy block is used in conjunction with the calibration pieces found here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1037301.

This block is used to determine the dimensional stability and accuracy of a calibrated filament. After calibrating the filament using the interlocking "C" shapes in the link above you then print this block using the same settings. The dimensions of 0.5" x 1.0" x 2.0" are important. While being dead on is always desirable the real intent is to make sure that dimensional variance in any direction stacks up consistently. For example a variance of .001 in the half inch direction should show up as a .002 in the 1" direction and .004 in the 2" direction. You want these values to be proportional for a good filament. If they are within .0005" for me then I consider it good. See the pictures.

The STL file is Cura scaled and oriented for printing.

I have been able to use this combination of calibration and accuracy objects to avoid using bad filament that would under extrude on the calibration and over extrude on the accuracy block. This also identifies for me my prime filaments for tight tolerance multi-part prints.

Laboratory PCR Tube Cooler for keeping you PCR reagents, RNA/DNA and reaction mixes cool while your doing your PCR prep. This accommodates 96 0.1-0.2 ml PCR tubes and 10 1.5ml tubes. It can also accommodate most PCR reagent vials (up to 10).

INSTRUCTIONS FOR USE:
Print the calibration piece and determine the amount of Vertical Shell offset that you need in order for your tubes to fit (approximately -0.15 to -0.20 mm for Craftware users). Use the same settings in printing the rest of the Main Body and Tube Holder. Fill with shaved ice up to the second line before placing the Tube holder on top.

You can also use plain water (if you don't have an ice maker). Fill the Main Body with distilled water up to the first line, then freeze. Before using, fill it with distilled cold water up to the 2nd line before placing the Tube holder on top.

The holder can keep your tubes cold between 30-60 minutes (approximate). Replenish ice as needed.

I still need to readjust this to fit PCR tube strips, but in the meantime, it may fit only single tubes.

The holes are canted at 15.9 degrees to accommodate the wedge shape of the foam.
This mount should work for other planes using Ston Bblue Airlines S/M mount. However I would change the angles of the holes to work your design.

description.text:
This style of shaft coupling can run you $150 a piece for each individual coupling, not counting the cost of the bronze or rubber spider. Now you can make your own.

The spider absorbs any misorientation of the shaft that could cause a bending-moment in the couplings; the spider will fail instead of the coupling and can simply be replaced, but with good alignment the coupling will last for many years.

This coupling is used often to transmit significant force as well.

This was designed for a 1.5" shaft, but you could edit the shaft diameter to account for many combinations of shafts, with say, a 2" maximum.

Ideal material is plain carbon steel for the couplings and bronze for the spider. This design could be machined or 3D printed; it's teeth are designed to be millable with a 1" endmill or smaller.

There is a keyway in each coupling, recommend using spring-steel as your key.

To hold the shaft on is a 3/8"-16 threaded hole, use with a set-screw.

Enjoy!

description.text:
This is a 3 part bracket to fit esteevens' fan duct on my rp3d Pangu Wooden i3 printer which originally had a standard 40mm unducted fan mounted forward of the extruder.

Should be fairly self explanitory how it fits together, M5 screws self thread into the main bracket and the circular top section of the drop-link. The fan is screwed to the drop-link with an M4 screw and nut, the nut fitting into the recess on the back of the drop-link to stop it turning. M3 screws attach the main bracket to the extruder mount.

Position the horizontal arm fan and drop link as necessary to get the duct in the right position. Don't forget about clearance at the far of the X axis.

I found it necessary to tweak the duct slightly by using some hot air where the ring connects to the blower and putting a slight bend in there to lift the end of the ring up so it's uniformly level and above the bed when mounted and extruder is at the Z-stop.

Edit: Added some additional files. "Tape Dispenser_tapewheel_hollow.stl" can be printed and fitted with a wooden dowel to act as an axle. I also separated the tape dispenser body and original tape wheel into individual STLs for selective printing. 
I'm still not totally sold on the current tape wheel design but I think the Dispenser body is pretty close to what I want.

title: Matchplate parts for Aluminum sand cast for Raspberry Pi Zero v 1.3 case
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Design for a case for the Raspberry Pi Zero version 1.3 to be sand cast in Aluminum.

This design has a "riser" to put the top of the CPU/Memory Package on package in contact with the top of the case. Heat dissipation fins that average 1 mm in width run along the short axis on the top.

As this is intended to be sand cast, there is a five degree draft to the vertical surfaces. The two halves of the matchplate have been scaled up to 101% which I understand is the standard shrinkage of Aluminum that is used in sand casting.

There are four ninety degree cones on the the pcb standoffs on the heat fin side, and four ninety degree cones on the underside of the bottom piece. The bottom piece should be drilled with a clearance hole for an M2.5 screw. There is enough material to counter sink these holes to allow for the screw to flush mount here. The top piece should have these cones drilled for threading for an M2.5 screw. For aluminum this is usually the 75% thread engagement size.

The riser for the cpu/memory package has been extended down to the surface of the board. This is so that it can be machined flat to the correct height. Casting it to the correct height may not result in proper contact with the cpu/memory package.

I am including the full sketchup model, as well as STL files of the two case halves in case you want to print it out to check out fitment with the Raspberry Pi Zero. I have not had a chance to try this out.

The matchplate is intended to be constructed by printing out the two halves, gluing them together and then gluing the result into some 6mm plywood.

Feed back from anyone with sand casting experience would be appreciated.

Licensing for commercial use can be negotiated.

Update!: Checked with a couple of people with experience in sand casting and aluminum and made some changes to make the resulting match plate work better. Updated description

title: Buzzer Support
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Your blinking flashing bot can now get an upgrade, it can talk too! This thing instructs you how to add a buzzer to your bot so that it can tell you when your build has completed, paused @ ZPos, or your safety cutoff has triggered. Very useful if you've quarantined your bot to another room, where it's difficult to hear it printing. Attach a 100dB voice to it and be launched out of your chair when your bot needs you! Also includes GCode support (see attached document), so you can add buzzes to your start/end.gcode. As this isn't something you print, please click on "I Made One" and submit a picture of your buzzer. Requirements:

  • Motherboard v2.4 http://wiki.makerbot.com/thingomatic-doc:makerbot-motherboard-2-4

  • Internal Drive Buzzer (see discussion below, note this is not the one suggested in makerbot's docs)

  • Jetty firmware V2.3 or higher: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15380
    • Optional: Gen 4 LCD Interface Buzzer: You require a Piezo Continuous Tone Internal Drive buzzer that will run off 5V and use no more than 20mA. This buzzer contains a circuit inside that produces a continuous fixed tone when powered. There are many buzzers that will work, I used the following 100dB buzzer mounted externally on the bot, and it's "Loud" (you can always tape over the hole to reduce volume):
    BRP4016L-12-C: http://www.icc-intervox.com/inc/Intervox_catalog/page17.pdf
    http://www.futureelectronics.com/en/technologies/passives/buzzers/Pages/5692009-BRP4016L-12-C.aspx?Language=en-US This will also work:
    http://search.digikey.com/us/en/products/PB-1408-1/433-1065-ND/1245336 Note: External drive and electromagnetic / coil buzzers and speakers will not work and could damage your Arduino Mega.

• Solder buzzer onto the Motherboard in the location labelled "Piezo".
    (I chose to mount mine outside of the case so it was louder, so I soldered wires and a connector to the motherboard instead)

  • Install Jetty firmware V2.3 or higher: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15380

  • If you require GCode support for controlling your buzzer, use this ReplicatorG: https://github.com/jetty840/ReplicatorG (Not required for the default Buzzing on Build Complete, [email protected] and Safety Cutout triggered)
    • Note: Signal on Build Complete, only occurs when building from SD Card. For building direct from a computer, add GCode "M214 I2 J3 K3" to your "end.gcode"

It's 5V continuous, the 20ma is because of the pin limitation.  So if you have a relay that's coil side requires less than 20ma, use that.  If it requires more, use a transistor to drive the coil. The 15% threshold was an arbitrary percent selected and not based on any published target.

I used Lulzbot's Dual Extruder Version 2 that was being sold for the TAZ 5. I find that setting the front extruder (closest to you - extruder 1) to be slightly higher than the rear extruder (away from you - extruder 0) gives best results. Otherwise the extruders get clogged from each others print. This adjustment has to be done manually.

I mostly used TinkerCAD to set the position of each model so that they both lined up perfecly. I just loaded and then saved as Cura automatically centered the model.

Using Cura I first loaded the "below threshold" stl file. then I loaded the "above threshold" stl file. After clicking on the first model I then right clicked on the second one and selected dual extrusion merge. You should get the two merged together as you see in the two images of Cura settings.

I also used Cura's "pause at height" plugin to switch filament color from blue to yellow of extruder set to states "below threshold" stl file (first loaded model).

If you are using the Lulzbot Taz 6 with the dual extruder and Lulzbot's recommended Cura rendering software be very careful to always check before printing that your gcode.start and gcode.end settings have the right gcode. You will find that those preamble and epilogue code (precode and post code) will disappear on certain settings and the TAZ 6 will start printing without calibrating - it won't do bed leveling and measuring of extruder height.

description.text:
Okay this is a remix of the original posted by Die_Bastelkammer. I have also included the .pdf of the original article that details the build as well as the sketchup files so you can make changes if you want. I live in a small town and wanted to be able to source all the the materials for the build locally. So I modified the T to accept 1/2" copper tubing for the elements and 1/2" EMT conduit for the boom. Turns out 1/2" conduit has a slightly larger ID than the 1/2" copper pipe. This antenna is pretty forgiving as far as how it's built is concerned and materials used so just cut the copper pipe to the proper lengths and slip it on the T until it touches the center box. This will provide the correct spacing for the element. Make sure you print @ 100% infill so that it is very rigid. I used PLA but ABS would work too. I also printed at .20 resolution.

This is a work in progress as I will be posting the final design of the center hub shortly.

After 6 months, I just created a threaded version. The thread used by the PINDA probe seems to be a ISO M8.1, which is not the same as a M8 rode.
There are two versions, "Pinda-Hat-v2.1.stl" with a standard thread size, and "Pinda-Hat-v2.1 - bigthread.stl" with bigger thread if you have some ABS shrinking much while printing. I personnaly printed the 2.1 version with 0.20 profile and it fits perfectly, screw pretty easily but tighten enough for it to stay on place. Enjoy :)
[/EDIT 05/01/17]

I designed this protective cap for the pinda probe of original Prusa i3 mk2 printer.

This cap is made to avoid the probe to grab unsticked parts or other printing issue above the printed layer, and to make it slide under it.

The center is just the size needed to hold the M8 thread, so I used a threaded rod to make a thread in ABS. Once in place, the black part of the pinda does almost not overreach the central hole, to minimize chance to pull something. No additional space is used below it. It's several mm from the block heater, that's the part I'm not 100 % sure yet.
I used very low resolution (0.05 mm) in order to make it smooth and to be sure to minimize any friction possible.
